1
00:00:14,208 --> 00:00:15,800
Quiet on the set.

2
00:00:17,478 --> 00:00:19,537
Scene one, take ten.
Marker.

3
00:00:26,821 --> 00:00:29,381
And action!

4
00:00:31,625 --> 00:00:33,593
Joel Levison's office.

5
00:00:33,661 --> 00:00:37,222
l'm sorry, he's not in yet.
May l take a message?

6
00:00:37,298 --> 00:00:40,096
- Mr. Levy, l'll tell him you called.
- Never say that.

7
00:00:40,167 --> 00:00:43,500
He's either in conference, in a meeting.
He's always in.

8
00:00:43,571 --> 00:00:45,766
- Who was that?
- Larry Levy.

9
00:00:47,141 --> 00:00:49,632
Was there anything in the trades
this morning?

10
00:00:49,710 --> 00:00:53,271
- l don't know. The mail's late.
- Go get them. Now!

11
00:00:53,347 --> 00:00:56,544
l want them back here
before he arrives.

12
00:01:11,499 --> 00:01:15,526
Griffin, hi. Adam Simon.

13
00:01:15,603 --> 00:01:17,969
We weren't supposed to meet
until next week, but--

14
00:01:18,038 --> 00:01:22,099
- l didn't know we were.
- l wanted to plant a seed in your head.

15
00:01:22,176 --> 00:01:24,667
- l'm booked up.
- Picture this.

16
00:01:24,745 --> 00:01:27,407
lt's a planet in the far future
with two suns.

17
00:01:27,481 --> 00:01:29,711
- Who plays the sons?
- No, suns. Large solar disks.

18
00:01:29,784 --> 00:01:31,718
Run this idea by Bonnie Sherow.

19
00:01:31,786 --> 00:01:35,187
The pictures they make these days
are all MTV. Cut, cut, cut.

20
00:01:35,256 --> 00:01:38,714
The opening shot of Touch of Evil
was six and a half minutes long.

21
00:01:38,793 --> 00:01:41,284
- Six and a half minutes?
- Three or four, anyway.

22
00:01:41,362 --> 00:01:44,559
He set up the whole picture
with that one tracking shot.

23
00:01:44,632 --> 00:01:47,032
My father was key grip on that shoot.

24
00:01:47,101 --> 00:01:51,299
What about Absolute Beginners?
That was an extraordinary shot.

25
00:01:51,372 --> 00:01:54,637
- Never heard of it.
- lt's an English film.

26
00:01:59,046 --> 00:02:02,140
- A Peligrino, please.
- l've got Calistoga.

27
00:02:02,216 --> 00:02:04,241
- Buck, how are you?
- Good. How you doin'?

28
00:02:04,318 --> 00:02:08,687
- Good. What have you got for me?
- Okay, here it is.

29
00:02:08,756 --> 00:02:11,589
- The Graduate, Part ll.
- Oh, good.

30
00:02:11,659 --> 00:02:14,685
Listen, the three principals
are still with us.

31
00:02:14,762 --> 00:02:20,223
Dustin Hoffman, Anne Bancroft,
Katharine Ross, 25 years later.

32
00:02:20,301 --> 00:02:25,261
And so are the characters,
Ben, Elaine and Mrs. Robinson.

33
00:02:25,339 --> 00:02:27,273
Ben and Elaine are married, still.

34
00:02:27,341 --> 00:02:32,040
They live in a big, spooky house
up in northern California somewhere.

35
00:02:32,112 --> 00:02:35,206
And Mrs. Robinson
lives with them...

36
00:02:35,282 --> 00:02:39,981
her aging mother
who's had a stroke...

37
00:02:40,054 --> 00:02:41,988
so she can't talk.

38
00:02:42,056 --> 00:02:45,617
- Will it be funny?
- lt'll be funny. Dark, weird and funny.

39
00:02:45,693 --> 00:02:49,060
And with a stroke.
Maybe it's not a stroke.

40
00:02:49,129 --> 00:02:51,791
l don't know what it is.
lt's a malady of some sort.

41
00:02:51,866 --> 00:02:55,461
She's up in the bedroom listening
to everything that happens.

42
00:02:55,536 --> 00:02:58,471
They've got a daughter
who's just graduated from college.

43
00:02:58,539 --> 00:03:02,873
Twenty-two, twenty-three-year-old,
like a Julia Roberts.

44
00:03:02,943 --> 00:03:04,968
Excuse me.
What should l do with these scripts?

45
00:03:05,045 --> 00:03:10,381
They go to Bonnie. And find out from
security how Adam Simon got on the lot.

46
00:03:10,451 --> 00:03:14,410
- l want to know.
- Adam Simon? Okay.

47
00:03:14,488 --> 00:03:17,582
Julia Roberts comes home,
their daughter, the graduate.

48
00:03:17,658 --> 00:03:19,489
The new graduate.

49
00:03:19,560 --> 00:03:22,222
Griffin loved it.
He wanted me to run it by you.

50
00:03:22,296 --> 00:03:27,632
- lt's a band of human survivors.
- Write this down for me.

51
00:03:27,701 --> 00:03:30,795
l can't process this.
Write it down for me.

52
00:03:30,871 --> 00:03:33,999
lt's not about words.
You have to visualize.

53
00:03:37,378 --> 00:03:41,474
Jimmy, are you okay?
What happened?

54
00:03:42,816 --> 00:03:46,343
- Are you all right?
- My name's Jimmy Chase.

55
00:03:48,389 --> 00:03:52,052
He came out of nowhere, ran right
in front of the cart. l never saw him.

56
00:03:57,031 --> 00:03:59,329
- That's Adam Simon.
- How you doin', kid?

57
00:04:08,742 --> 00:04:12,109
Rebecca DeMornay.
Actually, you're better looking.

58
00:04:12,179 --> 00:04:15,239
- No, l'm not Rebecca DeMornay.
- You're a dead ringer.

59
00:04:15,316 --> 00:04:17,011
Thank you very much.

60
00:04:17,084 --> 00:04:19,848
Do you know where
Joel Levison's office is?

61
00:04:19,920 --> 00:04:22,753
The head of the studio?

62
00:04:22,823 --> 00:04:24,757
lt's moving.
lt'll rip your heart out.

63
00:04:24,825 --> 00:04:29,694
This is the area where we make decisions
to give a green light to a picture.

64
00:04:29,763 --> 00:04:34,257
We're going to go 17 stories high.
We'll continue to use all Sony products.

65
00:04:34,335 --> 00:04:37,361
Domo arigato to the Sony products.

66
00:04:37,438 --> 00:04:41,966
lf you need someone to eat sashimi
with you, give me a ring.

67
00:04:48,215 --> 00:04:50,513
The traffic from Malibu
was impossible.

68
00:04:50,584 --> 00:04:54,179
- Good morning, Joel.
- Sandy, park the car, please.

69
00:04:54,254 --> 00:04:56,245
Good morning Marty, Annie.

70
00:04:58,392 --> 00:05:03,056
- What are the Japs doing here?
- What's this talk about heads rolling?

71
00:05:03,130 --> 00:05:06,258
The bank's putting screws to us.
Goldman's son is coming out from Boston.

72
00:05:06,333 --> 00:05:07,766
l don't like it.

73
00:05:07,835 --> 00:05:11,293
Reggie Goldman's a pipsqueak.
You can't be serious.

74
00:05:11,372 --> 00:05:15,604
Some changes are going on here.
That's always the way.

75
00:05:15,676 --> 00:05:18,509
lt happened at Paramount
three years ago.

76
00:05:18,579 --> 00:05:20,672
Columbia's going through it now.

77
00:05:20,748 --> 00:05:23,012
l hear we're looking
to replace Griffin.

78
00:05:23,083 --> 00:05:25,415
Griffin? l don't believe it.
With whom?

79
00:05:25,486 --> 00:05:28,887
Burke or Patrick.
Maybe Larry Levy.

80
00:05:28,956 --> 00:05:32,653
l want to know why
the security is lax.

81
00:05:32,726 --> 00:05:35,718
l'll talk to you later.
l'm in the middle of a pitch.

82
00:05:35,796 --> 00:05:37,957
Listen, go ahead.

83
00:05:38,032 --> 00:05:43,334
- lt's a TV star who goes on a safari.
- A TV star in a motion picture?

84
00:05:43,404 --> 00:05:48,341
- A TV star played by a movie star.
- A movie star playing a TV star.

85
00:05:48,409 --> 00:05:52,743
- Michelle, Bette, Lily.
- Dolly Parton would be good.

86
00:05:52,813 --> 00:05:58,080
- l like Goldie.
- Great, because we have a relationship.

87
00:05:58,152 --> 00:06:00,620
Goldie goes to Africa.

88
00:06:00,687 --> 00:06:06,387
- She's found by this tribe.
- Of small people.

89
00:06:06,460 --> 00:06:09,327
She's found and they worship her.

90
00:06:09,396 --> 00:06:14,197
lt's like The Gods Must Be Crazy
except the coke bottle is an actress.

91
00:06:14,268 --> 00:06:16,896
Right. lt's Out of Africa
meets Pretty Woman.

92
00:06:16,970 --> 00:06:20,531
She has to decide whether to stay
with the TV show...

93
00:06:20,607 --> 00:06:23,098
or save the tribe.

94
00:06:23,177 --> 00:06:26,146
- Where's Griffin Mill's office?
- Right here.

95
00:06:26,213 --> 00:06:29,148
- You're Martin Scorsese!
- No, but l know Harvey Keitel.

96
00:06:29,216 --> 00:06:32,708
l know you do.
l loved Cape Fear.

97
00:06:32,786 --> 00:06:35,482
My old man worked for Hitchcock.

98
00:06:35,556 --> 00:06:37,820
Rope. lt was a masterpiece.

99
00:06:37,891 --> 00:06:40,689
The story wasn't any good.
He shot the whole thing without cuts.

100
00:06:40,761 --> 00:06:42,661
l hate all this 'Cut, cut, cut!'

101
00:06:42,729 --> 00:06:48,224
What about Bertolucci, the great shot
with Winger in Sheltering Sky?

102
00:06:48,302 --> 00:06:50,361
l didn't see it.

103
00:06:53,740 --> 00:06:57,767
- l've been here since 8:00.
- l took a chance getting you this job.

104
00:06:57,845 --> 00:07:01,804
- Who were you with?
- l was with Alan Rudolph.

105
00:07:01,882 --> 00:07:06,785
- What were you doing with him?
- He asked me to have coffee.

106
00:07:06,854 --> 00:07:09,414
You're my assistant.
You don't get involved with writers.

107
00:07:09,490 --> 00:07:12,391
l wasn't getting involved. l was
listening to this amazing idea he had.

108
00:07:12,459 --> 00:07:14,984
That's interesting.
What's your pitch?

109
00:07:15,062 --> 00:07:18,498
- Does political scare you?
- Political doesn't scare me.

110
00:07:18,565 --> 00:07:21,261
Radical political scares me.
Political political scares me.

111
00:07:21,335 --> 00:07:24,862
This is politely politically radical,
but it's funny.

112
00:07:24,938 --> 00:07:29,238
- lt's a funny political thing.
- And it's a thriller, too, all at once.

113
00:07:29,309 --> 00:07:33,473
-What's the story?
-l want Bruce Willis. l can talk to him.

114
00:07:33,547 --> 00:07:37,005
lt's a story about a bad-guy senator.

115
00:07:37,084 --> 00:07:41,544
He's traveling around the country
on the country's dime, like Sununu did.

116
00:07:41,622 --> 00:07:44,090
lt's a cynical, political
thriller comedy.

117
00:07:44,158 --> 00:07:49,425
But it's got heart in the right spot.
Anyway, he has an accident.

118
00:07:49,496 --> 00:07:54,297
And he becomes clairvoyant,
like a psychic.

119
00:07:54,368 --> 00:07:57,496
So it's a psychic, political,
thriller comedy with a heart.

120
00:07:57,571 --> 00:08:01,905
With a heart, not unlike Ghost
meets Manchurian Candidate.

121
00:08:01,975 --> 00:08:05,502
- Go on, l'm listening.
- He starts reading people's minds.

122
00:08:05,579 --> 00:08:10,175
And when he gets to the President's mind
it's completely blank.

123
00:08:10,250 --> 00:08:12,480
- Can l get you anything?
- l'd like a beer, please.

124
00:08:12,553 --> 00:08:15,681
- We don't have beer.
- Red wine, please.

125
00:08:17,357 --> 00:08:22,418
Someone gets killed at the end.
They always do in political thrillers.

126
00:08:22,551 --> 00:08:26,783
- Griffin Mill's office.
- Can you put him on?

127
00:08:26,855 --> 00:08:30,586
- May l ask who's calling?
- l'd like to speak to Griffin Mill.

128
00:08:30,659 --> 00:08:34,857
He's in a meeting right now. l can take
your name and have him get back to you.

129
00:08:34,930 --> 00:08:38,297
- Excuse me?
- He'll get back to me?

130
00:08:38,367 --> 00:08:41,803
- Do you know how often l've heard this?
- Who is this?

131
00:08:41,870 --> 00:08:44,998
- lf he doesn't get back to me--
- Who was that?

132
00:08:45,073 --> 00:08:48,065
- l don't know. He didn't say.
- What do you mean?

133
00:08:48,143 --> 00:08:53,445
l don't know how you'll cast it. The
lead is a 50-year-old circus performer.

134
00:08:53,515 --> 00:08:55,881
Let me read the coverage.

135
00:08:55,951 --> 00:08:58,044
Are we still having lunch
with Aaron Camp?

136
00:08:58,120 --> 00:09:01,214
- What time?
- l made it for 1:00.

137
00:09:01,290 --> 00:09:03,724
- Bad day?
- He's having writer's block.

138
00:09:05,794 --> 00:09:10,254
You have a meeting with Hutter and
Frank South this afternoon at 3:00.

139
00:09:10,332 --> 00:09:14,029
l'll be here. Put this morning's
meetings on the computer. Thanks.

140
00:09:15,170 --> 00:09:18,230
- Are you going now?
- l'm going to see Levison.

141
00:09:18,307 --> 00:09:21,208
Order me a Caesar salad
and a Crystal Geyser.

142
00:09:29,284 --> 00:09:32,651
About 5:00? Thanks, Sandy.

143
00:09:32,721 --> 00:09:35,019
Hi, Sandy.

144
00:09:35,090 --> 00:09:38,218
You can't go in there!
He's in a meeting.

145
00:09:39,361 --> 00:09:42,228
lt's all right, Celia.

146
00:09:42,297 --> 00:09:45,926
l don't think you've met Reg Goldman.
You know his father Harvey.

147
00:09:46,001 --> 00:09:49,732
Yes, of course. Hi, Reg.
From the bank in Boston.

148
00:09:49,805 --> 00:09:54,868
- Reg is out here for a few weeks.
- Great. Business or pleasure?

149
00:09:54,943 --> 00:09:57,537
A little of both, l hope.

150
00:09:57,613 --> 00:09:59,410
Reg is thinking of producing.

151
00:09:59,481 --> 00:10:01,472
Really?

152
00:10:01,550 --> 00:10:03,848
Yeah. Beats work,
doesn't it, Griffin?

153
00:10:03,919 --> 00:10:06,285
l'd like to play some tennis.
Do you play tennis?

154
00:10:06,355 --> 00:10:08,721
Tennis? No.

155
00:10:08,790 --> 00:10:11,452
- l'm too busy.
- l was asking Walter.

156
00:10:11,527 --> 00:10:13,859
Do you know Meg Ryan?

157
00:10:13,929 --> 00:10:15,897
ls she seeing somebody?

158
00:10:17,199 --> 00:10:19,565
Yeah, Reg. She's married.

159
00:10:20,769 --> 00:10:22,202
Shit.

160
00:10:22,271 --> 00:10:24,933
What about Winona Ryder?

161
00:10:25,007 --> 00:10:29,876
You know, actually,
Walter is the guy to talk to.

162
00:10:29,945 --> 00:10:32,311
Walter's got everybody's number.

163
00:10:32,381 --> 00:10:36,477
- Was there anything?
- No. You're real busy.

164
00:10:36,552 --> 00:10:39,919
l want that number, goddamn it.
l want that number.

165
00:10:39,988 --> 00:10:43,583
Oh, boy. What about this one?
Has she done anything?

166
00:10:44,726 --> 00:10:46,159
Celia.

167
00:10:47,563 --> 00:10:50,555
Griffin, don't ask.

168
00:10:50,632 --> 00:10:55,092
Don't ask, you don't know?
Or don't ask, l don't want to know?

169
00:10:55,170 --> 00:10:57,468
Just don't ask.

170
00:10:58,574 --> 00:11:03,341
lf it's Reggie Goldman
you're concerned about, forget it.

171
00:11:03,412 --> 00:11:05,903
But be nice to him. He represents
a lot of money to this company.

172
00:11:05,981 --> 00:11:09,041
lt's not Reggie Goldman
l'm worried about.

173
00:11:09,117 --> 00:11:11,677
- lt's Larry Levy.
- Larry Levy?

174
00:11:12,654 --> 00:11:15,088
Larry Levy's at Fox, isn't he?

175
00:11:16,959 --> 00:11:19,189
Come on, Celia.

176
00:11:19,261 --> 00:11:22,389
There's a call for Celia
on line one.

177
00:11:22,464 --> 00:11:25,900
- Should l be looking for a job?
- Celia, are you there?

178
00:11:25,968 --> 00:11:30,302
Joel Levison's office.
Oh, Brad. Yeah.

179
00:11:30,372 --> 00:11:31,896
What?

180
00:11:31,974 --> 00:11:36,468
No, we couldn't sign Angelica Huston
for that. She's booked for two years.

181
00:11:36,578 --> 00:11:41,174
Like a ghost story,
but it's not like Ghost.

182
00:11:44,653 --> 00:11:46,848
lt's a supernatural thing.

183
00:11:49,324 --> 00:11:52,054
Joel, Griffin Mill.
A friend of Jennifer's.

184
00:11:52,127 --> 00:11:55,255
No. You're Griffin Mill?
Really?

185
00:11:55,330 --> 00:11:57,264
Good to see you.
l'm a big fan of yours.

186
00:11:57,332 --> 00:11:59,994
- l have that tie.
- You do?

187
00:12:06,441 --> 00:12:08,568
Did you order for me?

188
00:12:11,013 --> 00:12:14,744
Hi. Lunching with the enemy.

189
00:12:14,816 --> 00:12:16,784
Oh, come on.

190
00:12:16,852 --> 00:12:19,980
So what's this we hear
about Larry Levy?

191
00:12:20,055 --> 00:12:23,718
Larry Levy? lf he had half a brain,
he'd be dangerous.

192
00:12:25,661 --> 00:12:28,027
Aaron says he's coming
to the studio.

193
00:12:28,096 --> 00:12:32,760
Aaron says? Why would you believe
anything he says?

194
00:12:32,834 --> 00:12:35,564
He said it with authority.

195
00:12:35,637 --> 00:12:40,404
He's over there with Angelica Huston
and John Cusack.

196
00:12:40,475 --> 00:12:43,569
He's in over his head.
He's gonna drown over there.

197
00:12:44,613 --> 00:12:47,138
He's the golden boy at Fox these days.

198
00:12:47,215 --> 00:12:50,082
Did you see that thing on him
in Variety last week?

199
00:12:50,152 --> 00:12:51,676
Two pages.

200
00:12:51,753 --> 00:12:55,689
Angelica, Griffin Mill.
Good to see you. You're looking great.

201
00:12:55,757 --> 00:12:58,726
Johnny, Griffin Mill.
A big fan of yours.

202
00:12:58,794 --> 00:13:01,854
- You gonna be in Telluride this year?
- Probably in Park City.

203
00:13:01,930 --> 00:13:04,125
Great. We'll see you there.

204
00:13:05,767 --> 00:13:11,205
- What's happening with Glass Box?
- Let's not talk about Hollywood.

205
00:13:11,273 --> 00:13:13,833
We're educated people.

206
00:13:18,947 --> 00:13:21,074
l'll call you later.

207
00:13:53,448 --> 00:13:55,916
- Talk to somebody about this.
- What?

208
00:13:55,984 --> 00:13:58,817
- You've gotten 5 postcards in 2 weeks.
- Seven, actually.

209
00:13:58,887 --> 00:14:01,481
Why don't you talk to Studio Security?

210
00:14:01,556 --> 00:14:03,683
l should call Walter Stuckel
and say what?

211
00:14:03,759 --> 00:14:08,458
'Someone's sending me poison letters
and l would like for you to make me...

212
00:14:08,530 --> 00:14:12,159
the object of more ridicule now that
things are really shaky for me here.(

213
00:14:12,234 --> 00:14:13,667
l don't think so.

214
00:14:13,735 --> 00:14:15,760
l think they're coming from a writer.

215
00:14:15,837 --> 00:14:17,828
- Which one?
- Take your pick.

216
00:14:20,342 --> 00:14:22,708
- ls there anything else?
- Yes, your attorney phoned.

217
00:14:22,778 --> 00:14:25,611
He wants you to attend a party
at his house tonight.

218
00:14:25,680 --> 00:14:28,649
- Tell him l'm at a screening.
- Not that attorney. lt's Dick Mellen.

219
00:14:28,717 --> 00:14:30,150
What time?

220
00:14:30,218 --> 00:14:33,187
Cocktails at 7:30, dinner at 8:00.
Bring a date.

221
00:14:33,255 --> 00:14:35,519
And Bonnie Sherow is here to see you.

222
00:14:35,590 --> 00:14:38,525
Send her in.
Oh, here she is.

223
00:14:38,593 --> 00:14:41,687
Can we go to the Springs this weekend?

224
00:14:41,763 --> 00:14:46,325
l want to have a massage,
a long soak in a hot tub...

225
00:14:46,401 --> 00:14:49,632
and have Margaritas administered
intravenously.

226
00:14:49,704 --> 00:14:51,934
l have a party at Dick Mellen's.
You want to come?

227
00:14:52,007 --> 00:14:54,567
God, movie stars and power players.

228
00:14:54,643 --> 00:14:57,578
- And Vodka.
- Sure.

229
00:14:57,646 --> 00:15:00,843
lt'll be an early dinner,
and we'll go to my place afterwards.

230
00:15:00,916 --> 00:15:02,850
