299
00:19:19,164 --> 00:19:21,894
The camera moves in
on the nostrils of the horse...

300
00:19:21,967 --> 00:19:25,300
as the buckboard begins to shake.(

301
00:19:25,370 --> 00:19:29,204
God! Do you believe that?
Steve recommended that script.

302
00:19:29,274 --> 00:19:33,108
He says they're hot for it at Universal.
They're gonna have a bidding war.

303
00:19:33,178 --> 00:19:36,705
l heard a pitch today. lt wasn't bad.
Stuck on a story point, though.

304
00:19:36,782 --> 00:19:41,446
- l'm a story editor. Go.
- New York City, big advertising agency.

305
00:19:41,520 --> 00:19:44,648
An account executive makes
a presentation to a potential client.

306
00:19:44,723 --> 00:19:47,191
The client promises
to get back to him.

307
00:19:47,259 --> 00:19:49,784
- Does it have to be advertising?
- That's not the problem.

308
00:19:49,862 --> 00:19:53,696
The account executive keeps waiting
for the client to call him back...

309
00:19:53,765 --> 00:19:57,292
to tell him what he thought
of the idea, if he got the job or not.

310
00:19:57,369 --> 00:19:59,769
But the client never calls.

311
00:19:59,838 --> 00:20:04,707
The account executive gets so pissed off
and frustrated, he becomes obsessive.

312
00:20:04,776 --> 00:20:08,212
- He decides to drive the client crazy.
- What does he do?

313
00:20:08,280 --> 00:20:12,808
Sends him threatening postcards.
lt's not important.

314
00:20:12,885 --> 00:20:16,821
Here's the problem.
How long do you think...

315
00:20:16,889 --> 00:20:20,381
the account executive
harasses the client...

316
00:20:20,459 --> 00:20:22,791
before he becomes dangerous?

317
00:20:22,861 --> 00:20:25,887
- Does it have to be advertising?
- How long?

318
00:20:25,964 --> 00:20:28,455
lf it were me--

319
00:20:28,533 --> 00:20:30,228
One month?

320
00:20:30,302 --> 00:20:32,964
Three months.
No, more. Five months.

321
00:20:33,038 --> 00:20:35,871
- To be dangerous, five months.
- That's what l thought.

322
00:20:35,941 --> 00:20:38,102
- Who's the writer?
- l don't know.

323
00:20:38,176 --> 00:20:40,804
You don't know the writer
who pitched you the idea?

324
00:20:40,879 --> 00:20:44,406
l don't know his name.
lt's a couple kids.

325
00:20:45,851 --> 00:20:47,318
TV writers.

326
00:20:48,820 --> 00:20:52,813
Can we go to bed now?
l'm starting to wrinkle.

327
00:21:00,265 --> 00:21:02,199
- See you tomorrow afternoon.
- Absolutely.

328
00:21:02,267 --> 00:21:05,134
Burt, Larry Levy. l hope you don't
remember me, and if you do...

329
00:21:05,203 --> 00:21:09,503
l hope there are no hard feelings,
l was working for Gassner then.

330
00:21:14,613 --> 00:21:16,672
Take care.

331
00:21:16,748 --> 00:21:19,478
- Who was that?
- An exec over at Fox.

332
00:21:19,551 --> 00:21:21,644
Was until breakfast, anyway.

333
00:21:30,128 --> 00:21:32,858
- Good morning, Mr. Mill.
- Hi, Susan. How are you?

334
00:21:32,931 --> 00:21:35,559
l'm with Joel.

335
00:21:35,634 --> 00:21:38,728
- Hi, Burt. Griffin Mill.
- Good to see you.

336
00:21:38,804 --> 00:21:41,068
Hi, Charles. How are you?

337
00:21:41,139 --> 00:21:43,630
- Asshole.
- One of a breed.

338
00:21:45,744 --> 00:21:50,204
Actually, he's not. There's a whole
breed of them. They're breeding them.

339
00:21:50,282 --> 00:21:53,149
Joel, you're losing your touch,
scheduling meetings so close together.

340
00:21:53,218 --> 00:21:55,686
That guy didn't have time
to finish his breakfast.

341
00:21:55,754 --> 00:21:58,154
He'd already eaten.
Gets up early.

342
00:21:59,358 --> 00:22:02,691
- You went to Mellen's last night.
- Take this away, please. Yes, l did.

343
00:22:02,761 --> 00:22:06,492
- How is he?
- l'd like a Vitelle water.

344
00:22:06,565 --> 00:22:08,590
He's fine.

345
00:22:08,667 --> 00:22:10,897
You left early. Why?

346
00:22:10,969 --> 00:22:14,803
We had to work
on the museum party.

347
00:22:14,873 --> 00:22:17,671
l will not work for Larry Levy.

348
00:22:17,743 --> 00:22:20,075
l'm not asking you to.

349
00:22:21,346 --> 00:22:24,679
l report to you. lf l have to report
to Larry Levy, l quit.

350
00:22:27,019 --> 00:22:30,511
You can't quit.
l won't let you quit.

351
00:22:30,589 --> 00:22:33,285
You have a year and a half on your
contract. l'll sue you for breach...

352
00:22:33,358 --> 00:22:36,691
if you don't show up in the office
every day, with a smile.

353
00:22:38,030 --> 00:22:40,294
Why Levy?

354
00:22:40,365 --> 00:22:42,765
Levy was available.

355
00:22:42,834 --> 00:22:45,268
He's good on material,
you're good with writers.

356
00:22:45,337 --> 00:22:47,965
We're a team. He's a new member
of the team, that's all.

357
00:22:49,107 --> 00:22:51,268
He can make us all look good.

358
00:22:51,343 --> 00:22:54,335
This is a wine glass. Can l have
my water in a water glass, please?

359
00:22:55,680 --> 00:22:57,170
Well?

360
00:22:57,249 --> 00:23:00,309
l'll have to think about it.

361
00:23:00,385 --> 00:23:02,285
l want an answer this afternoon.

362
00:23:02,354 --> 00:23:05,050
l have to go out to Palmdale.

363
00:23:05,123 --> 00:23:08,058
The director of Lonely Room
is giving Lily a hard time.

364
00:23:09,361 --> 00:23:13,058
- l'll be back around 5:00.
- So call after 5:00.

365
00:23:13,131 --> 00:23:15,497
l'll get back to you.

366
00:23:15,567 --> 00:23:19,628
...you haven't died.
See, he's still hanging on.

367
00:23:32,184 --> 00:23:35,517
Griffin, Joel Levison on line 2.
l'll put it through.

368
00:23:35,587 --> 00:23:38,317
- l'll get back to him.
- Tell Joel you'll get back to him?

369
00:23:38,390 --> 00:23:41,951
Yeah. l want to hear
what he's got to say.

370
00:23:51,603 --> 00:23:54,731
- How did this get here?
- The mail.

371
00:23:54,806 --> 00:23:57,707
But this does not have a postmark.
This was hand-delivered.

372
00:23:57,776 --> 00:23:59,835
Not to me.
lt came with the mail.

373
00:23:59,911 --> 00:24:01,344
Jimmy?

374
00:24:03,815 --> 00:24:06,875
Do you know anything about this?
Who delivered it? Where it came from?

375
00:24:06,952 --> 00:24:09,318
Mail room?

376
00:24:09,387 --> 00:24:12,083
But l want to know how it got
to the goddamn mail room.

377
00:24:12,157 --> 00:24:14,853
- Find out and get back to me.
- Okay, sure.

378
00:24:14,926 --> 00:24:18,760
- You go with him.
- You want me to go to the mail room?

379
00:24:18,830 --> 00:24:21,025
l want you to go to the mail room.
And while you're there...

380
00:24:21,099 --> 00:24:24,500
l would like a copy of
The Lonely Room rewrites...

381
00:24:24,569 --> 00:24:27,265
in white pages,
no color.

382
00:24:27,339 --> 00:24:29,864
- Find out how this got in my mail.
- Yes, sir.

383
00:24:29,941 --> 00:24:33,877
- You'll get your own phones?
- l can get my own phones.

384
00:24:40,619 --> 00:24:42,780
Son of a bitch!
Five months.

385
00:24:42,854 --> 00:24:46,290
One, two, three, four, five.

386
00:24:49,261 --> 00:24:52,025
Richard Fueller.
David Lucas.

387
00:24:55,333 --> 00:24:59,269
Cal Winstrom. David Kahane.
Sammy Tettleton.

388
00:25:05,110 --> 00:25:06,577
lncoming.

389
00:25:10,348 --> 00:25:13,840
lncoming. Unreturned calls.

390
00:25:13,919 --> 00:25:15,477
Bill Lyndstrom.

391
00:25:16,721 --> 00:25:19,121
Nancy Franklin.
Wouldn't be a woman.

392
00:25:19,191 --> 00:25:21,125
David Kahane.

393
00:25:33,838 --> 00:25:35,465
Lyndstrom.

394
00:25:37,642 --> 00:25:40,076
Strategic Planning.
Wouldn't be him.

395
00:25:40,145 --> 00:25:43,637
What was that other guy's name?

396
00:25:43,715 --> 00:25:45,148
Kahane.

397
00:25:47,419 --> 00:25:51,150
Kaltrime. Kahane.

398
00:25:51,223 --> 00:25:53,183
'Unproduced.'
Gotcha!

399
00:26:50,640 --> 00:26:53,803
- Hello.
- Hello. ls David Kahane there?

400
00:26:53,876 --> 00:26:55,309
David!

401
00:27:03,186 --> 00:27:07,179
l'm sorry. l forgot.
He's gone out. Who's this?

402
00:27:07,257 --> 00:27:10,317
- This is Griffin Mill.
- Oh, the dead man.

403
00:27:10,393 --> 00:27:13,920
- What did you say?
- Oh, nothing.

404
00:27:13,997 --> 00:27:19,629
- About me being a dead man?
- Just a nickname David has for you.

405
00:27:19,702 --> 00:27:23,468
l see.
That's a funny nickname.

406
00:27:23,539 --> 00:27:27,475
l suppose your husband doesn't like me
very much.

407
00:27:27,543 --> 00:27:29,738
l don't have a husband.

408
00:27:29,812 --> 00:27:31,939
l suppose David doesn't like me
very much.

409
00:27:32,015 --> 00:27:34,245
David's gone to the cinema.

410
00:27:34,317 --> 00:27:38,549
- When will he be back?
- When the film's over, l presume.

411
00:27:38,621 --> 00:27:41,317
And you are?

412
00:27:41,391 --> 00:27:44,121
- June.
- June?

413
00:27:44,193 --> 00:27:46,457
Here we go.
You want to know my last name.

414
00:27:46,529 --> 00:27:50,465
- No one can pronounce it.
- Try me.

415
00:27:50,533 --> 00:27:52,023
Gudmundsdottir.

416
00:27:52,101 --> 00:27:53,830
Gudmundsdottir.

417
00:27:57,173 --> 00:27:59,835
- How's that?
- Very good.

418
00:27:59,909 --> 00:28:01,342
Thanks.

419
00:28:02,645 --> 00:28:06,445
- What do people usually say?
- Don't ask.

420
00:28:06,516 --> 00:28:11,579
Anything from Good Dog's Water
to Goulash Wallop.

421
00:28:13,489 --> 00:28:15,821
- You English?
- Yep.

422
00:28:15,892 --> 00:28:18,224
Well, no, not really.

423
00:28:18,294 --> 00:28:21,161
Where are you sort of not from?

424
00:28:21,230 --> 00:28:25,189
Do you want the long story
or the short one?

425
00:28:25,268 --> 00:28:27,395
- The long one.
- No, you'd never believe it.

426
00:28:27,470 --> 00:28:31,429
- The short one's lceland.
- lceland?

427
00:28:31,507 --> 00:28:34,999
l didn't know anyone came from lceland.
l thought it was just a block of ice.

428
00:28:35,078 --> 00:28:37,444
lt's very green, actually.

429
00:28:37,513 --> 00:28:40,175
Really? l thought that was Greenland.

430
00:28:40,249 --> 00:28:44,845
No, Greenland's very icy.
lceland's very green.

431
00:28:44,921 --> 00:28:48,379
They switched names to fool the Vikings
who tried to steal their women.

432
00:28:48,458 --> 00:28:49,891
l see.

433
00:28:49,959 --> 00:28:52,894
No. Blue sea.

434
00:28:52,962 --> 00:28:54,930
Red sea.

435
00:28:54,997 --> 00:28:58,228
- No red.
- You're a painter.

436
00:28:58,301 --> 00:29:00,269
How did you guess?

437
00:29:01,871 --> 00:29:04,339
What movie did David go to see?

438
00:29:04,407 --> 00:29:08,309
He went to the Rialto in Pasadena.
He always goes there.

439
00:29:08,378 --> 00:29:10,278
What's showing?

440
00:29:10,346 --> 00:29:14,339
Bicycle Thief, l think.

441
00:29:14,417 --> 00:29:16,851
lt's a good movie.
Have you seen it?

442
00:29:18,087 --> 00:29:20,385
l don't go to the movies.

443
00:29:20,456 --> 00:29:21,889
Why not?

444
00:29:29,766 --> 00:29:32,098
Life is too short.

445
00:29:32,168 --> 00:29:34,693
l've got to hang up now.

446
00:30:59,789 --> 00:31:01,723
David Kahane!

447
00:31:01,791 --> 00:31:04,351
You have the wrong guy, man.

448
00:31:25,414 --> 00:31:28,212
David Kahane.
Griffin Mill.

449
00:31:29,819 --> 00:31:31,980
Griffin Mill.

450
00:31:32,054 --> 00:31:33,578
Yeah?

451
00:31:33,656 --> 00:31:35,851
Great movie, huh?

452
00:31:35,925 --> 00:31:39,827
lt's refreshing to see something like
this after all these cop movies...

453
00:31:39,896 --> 00:31:44,390
and, you know,
things we do.

454
00:31:44,467 --> 00:31:47,561
- Maybe we'll do a remake of this.
- You'd probably give it a happy ending.

455
00:31:47,637 --> 00:31:49,662
No, we'd keep it pure.

456
00:31:49,739 --> 00:31:51,673
Pure, right.

457
00:31:51,741 --> 00:31:55,268
- You want to write it?
- Don't fuck with me.

458
00:31:55,344 --> 00:31:57,904
l'm not fucking with you.
Didn't l say l'd get back to you?

459
00:31:57,980 --> 00:32:01,472
Yeah, about six months ago.
l thought you'd forgotten.

460
00:32:01,551 --> 00:32:04,247
You were angry.

461
00:32:04,320 --> 00:32:05,753
Maybe.

462
00:32:05,821 --> 00:32:08,153
Do you want to talk about it?

463
00:32:08,224 --> 00:32:10,749
- Okay, sure.
- Great.

464
00:32:10,826 --> 00:32:14,091
Let's let the studio
buy us a drink.

465
00:32:16,499 --> 00:32:20,492
lf you don't mind a place where you
don't have any suck with the maitre d'.

466
00:32:20,570 --> 00:32:23,164
- l know a bar down the street.
