Have you ever been to Japan?

468
00:32:33,349 --> 00:32:37,547
Yes. l was there once on
a location scout with Steven Spielberg.

469
00:32:37,620 --> 00:32:40,054
l lived there for a year.

470
00:32:40,122 --> 00:32:42,283
Student year abroad.

471
00:32:42,358 --> 00:32:45,191
l wish l'd done that.

472
00:32:45,261 --> 00:32:48,594
l think about it a lot.
l'll never forget it.

473
00:32:48,664 --> 00:32:51,189
You should write about it.

474
00:32:51,267 --> 00:32:53,827
l did.
Don't you remember?

475
00:32:55,037 --> 00:32:56,470
What?

476
00:32:58,774 --> 00:33:03,905
My idea about the American student
who goes to Japan.

477
00:33:03,980 --> 00:33:07,143
That was my pitch, the one you were
supposed to get back to me on.

478
00:33:07,216 --> 00:33:10,083
- You don't remember, do you?
- Of course l remember.

479
00:33:12,521 --> 00:33:15,149
You never got back to me.

480
00:33:15,224 --> 00:33:17,283
Listen.

481
00:33:17,360 --> 00:33:22,491
l was an asshole, all right?
lt comes with the job.

482
00:33:22,565 --> 00:33:24,692
l'm really sorry.

483
00:33:26,969 --> 00:33:30,166
l know how angry you must've been.
l'll make it up to you.

484
00:33:30,239 --> 00:33:31,831
That's why l'm here.

485
00:33:31,907 --> 00:33:35,434
l'm gonna give you a deal, David.

486
00:33:35,511 --> 00:33:39,208
l won't guarantee you l'll make
the movie, but l will give you a shot.

487
00:33:43,085 --> 00:33:47,920
Let's just stop all the postcard shit,
all right?

488
00:33:47,990 --> 00:33:50,788
l'm here to say
that l would like...

489
00:33:50,860 --> 00:33:52,794
to start over.

490
00:33:54,430 --> 00:33:55,863
Friends.

491
00:33:57,633 --> 00:34:00,363
Fuck you, man.
You're a liar.

492
00:34:00,436 --> 00:34:02,427
You're stepping over the line.

493
00:34:02,505 --> 00:34:04,735
You didn't come here
to see The Bicycle Thief.

494
00:34:04,807 --> 00:34:07,935
You came in five minutes
before the picture ended.

495
00:34:08,010 --> 00:34:10,444
Nearly tripped over my feet.

496
00:34:11,814 --> 00:34:13,748
Did you call my house?

497
00:34:15,718 --> 00:34:17,618
Speak to the lce Queen?

498
00:34:19,321 --> 00:34:22,586
You'd like her.
She's a lot like you.

499
00:34:22,658 --> 00:34:24,091
All heart.

500
00:34:30,232 --> 00:34:34,430
You're on my list, pal.
Nothing's gonna change that.

501
00:34:38,307 --> 00:34:41,936
See you in the next reel, asshole.

502
00:35:29,795 --> 00:35:33,731
lt's a nice boat you got there,
movie exec.

503
00:35:33,799 --> 00:35:37,098
lt's me, the writer.
Still want to buy my story?

504
00:35:37,169 --> 00:35:40,696
l told you l'd deal. Stop by the studio.
We'll work something out.

505
00:35:40,773 --> 00:35:43,674
And who will l ask for?

506
00:35:43,742 --> 00:35:45,175
Larry Levy?

507
00:35:47,179 --> 00:35:49,170
What's Larry Levy got to do with this?

508
00:35:50,249 --> 00:35:52,547
- How do you know about Larry Levy?
- Don't you read the trades?

509
00:35:52,618 --> 00:35:55,815
New York Times business section?
He's movin' in, you're movin' out.

510
00:35:55,888 --> 00:35:58,618
You can't make a deal, they say.
Yesterday's news.

511
00:35:58,690 --> 00:36:00,624
Wait a minute.

512
00:36:02,060 --> 00:36:04,551
Can l borrow your mobile phone?

513
00:36:04,630 --> 00:36:08,191
Larry Levy.
Larry, David Kahane here.

514
00:36:08,267 --> 00:36:12,203
Guess who's making promises
about getting pictures made...

515
00:36:12,271 --> 00:36:14,865
to writers in parking lots?

516
00:36:14,940 --> 00:36:17,966
Guess what dumb
son of a bitch executive...

517
00:36:18,043 --> 00:36:22,139
is trying to take advantage of me?

518
00:36:22,214 --> 00:36:25,980
Do you realize how unstoppable
this guy is?

519
00:36:26,051 --> 00:36:28,383
You know,
l cannot wait...

520
00:36:28,453 --> 00:36:33,481
to tell the world that when Griffin Mill
can't cut the pressure at work...

521
00:36:33,559 --> 00:36:36,585
he drives out to Pasadena...

522
00:36:36,662 --> 00:36:39,563
to pick fights with writers.

523
00:36:40,899 --> 00:36:42,924
Tell Larry Levy to call me.

524
00:36:43,001 --> 00:36:48,439
The word is out that he's going to start
making meaningful pictures for a change.

525
00:36:48,507 --> 00:36:51,670
Let's forget this.
Just stop all the postcard shit!

526
00:36:51,743 --> 00:36:53,973
l don't write postcards!
l write scripts!

527
00:36:54,046 --> 00:36:57,277
- We're both wrong.
- No, you're wrong, buddy!

528
00:36:57,349 --> 00:37:00,011
You're in over your head.
That's why you're losing your job.

529
00:37:00,085 --> 00:37:02,212
Then what are you gonna do?

530
00:37:03,355 --> 00:37:05,721
l can write.
What can you do?

531
00:37:10,495 --> 00:37:12,725
l said, let's forget this.

532
00:37:17,469 --> 00:37:19,460
Ah, shit.

533
00:37:21,573 --> 00:37:23,768
Mill, you okay?

534
00:37:32,217 --> 00:37:35,050
Keep it to yourself!

535
00:37:35,120 --> 00:37:37,714
Keep it to yourself!

536
00:38:03,382 --> 00:38:04,815
Kahane?

537
00:39:25,931 --> 00:39:29,731
That's interesting.
Who's writing this movie?

538
00:39:29,801 --> 00:39:33,328
Who wrote the new ending
to Fatal Attraction? The audience.

539
00:39:33,405 --> 00:39:36,397
A million screenwriters
from the audience wrote that.

540
00:39:36,475 --> 00:39:40,309
Who's to say what it would have done
if you had left the original ending?

541
00:39:40,379 --> 00:39:44,281
You're right, but you can say that it's
done almost 300 million worldwide...

542
00:39:44,349 --> 00:39:46,681
with the new ending.

543
00:39:46,818 --> 00:39:50,447
Larry Levy, l don't believe you've met
my assistant, Whitney Gersh.

544
00:39:50,522 --> 00:39:53,082
- No, l haven't.
- lt's a pleasure to meet you.

545
00:39:55,260 --> 00:39:57,922
How's your picture?
lt just tested last week.

546
00:39:57,996 --> 00:40:01,625
lt's doing well.
lt was our first test.

547
00:40:01,700 --> 00:40:03,600
Excuse me, Walter.

548
00:40:03,668 --> 00:40:08,071
Joel, Griffin isn't in, but l think
we really have to start this meeting.

549
00:40:08,140 --> 00:40:10,404
Okay, Celia. Thank you.

550
00:40:13,111 --> 00:40:15,341
Remember a movie called D.O.A.?

551
00:40:15,414 --> 00:40:17,609
Sure l do.
Eddie O'Brien and Pam Britton.

552
00:40:17,682 --> 00:40:21,174
Disney did a remake in '87 or '88.

553
00:40:21,253 --> 00:40:24,086
l think we've got
pretty much the same situation here.

554
00:40:24,156 --> 00:40:26,624
Keep our noses clean, Walter.

555
00:40:30,095 --> 00:40:32,586
lt's a shame to waste a picture.

556
00:40:32,664 --> 00:40:36,896
Who said we're wasting the picture?
Where did that come from?

557
00:40:36,968 --> 00:40:39,766
You know what's interesting?
We're all too busy--

558
00:40:39,838 --> 00:40:44,707
Griffin, you're really late.
They're waiting inside.

559
00:40:44,776 --> 00:40:48,212
To actually rub shoulders
with the great unwashed?

560
00:40:48,280 --> 00:40:51,545
We need to give them
the kind of pictures they want...

561
00:40:51,616 --> 00:40:53,743
not the kind
writers want to give them.

562
00:41:01,093 --> 00:41:04,085
- Hello. Sorry l'm late.
- You certainly are.

563
00:41:08,100 --> 00:41:10,330
A few minutes in the office
would be fine.

564
00:41:11,236 --> 00:41:13,636
Griffin, you missed
the formal welcoming ceremony.

565
00:41:13,705 --> 00:41:16,697
You know Larry Levy.

566
00:41:16,775 --> 00:41:18,800
Of course. Hi, Larry.

567
00:41:20,212 --> 00:41:21,645
Hi, Griffin.

568
00:41:21,713 --> 00:41:23,647
Larry was able to leave Fox
a week earlier than he thought...

569
00:41:23,715 --> 00:41:25,842
and has come aboard
as of this morning.

570
00:41:25,917 --> 00:41:30,980
- Great. Let's start.
- Larry was in the middle of something.

571
00:41:31,056 --> 00:41:34,651
No, l wasn't. l was just killing time
waiting for Griffin.

572
00:41:34,726 --> 00:41:37,752
No, finish.
What were you saying?

573
00:41:37,829 --> 00:41:42,266
l was saying l've yet to meet a writer
who could change water into wine...

574
00:41:42,334 --> 00:41:44,825
and we have a tendency
to treat them like that.

575
00:41:45,904 --> 00:41:48,168
Not at this studio.

576
00:41:48,240 --> 00:41:52,176
A million and a half of these scripts.
lt's nuts.

577
00:41:52,244 --> 00:41:54,576
And l think avoidable.

578
00:41:54,646 --> 00:41:58,639
Let me ask you. When was the last time
you bought a ticket to see a movie?

579
00:41:58,717 --> 00:42:02,653
- You actually paid your own money?
- Last night.

580
00:42:02,721 --> 00:42:04,916
Pasadena. The Bicycle Thief.

581
00:42:04,990 --> 00:42:08,187
- You saw The Bicycle Thief?
- l love that. lt's a great film.

582
00:42:08,260 --> 00:42:11,058
lt's an art movie. lt doesn't count.
We're talking about movie movies.

583
00:42:11,129 --> 00:42:13,063
Jesus, people.

584
00:42:13,131 --> 00:42:16,032
l'm just saying there's time
and money to be saved...

585
00:42:16,101 --> 00:42:18,831
if we came up with these stories
on our own.

586
00:42:18,904 --> 00:42:21,930
- Where are these stories coming from?
- Anywhere. lt doesn't matter.

587
00:42:23,508 --> 00:42:26,375
The newspaper.
Pick any story.

588
00:42:29,614 --> 00:42:32,674
'lmmigrants protest budget cuts
in literacy program.'

589
00:42:32,751 --> 00:42:36,209
Human spirit overcoming human adversity.
Sounds like Horatio Alger in the barrio.

590
00:42:36,288 --> 00:42:39,280
Put Jimmy Smits in it and you've got
a sexy Stand and Deliver.

591
00:42:39,357 --> 00:42:42,724
- Next. Come on.
- This isn't my field.

592
00:42:42,794 --> 00:42:45,524
lt doesn't matter. Give it a shot.
You can't lose here.

593
00:42:48,533 --> 00:42:52,833
How about 'Mud slide kills 60
in slums of Chili'?

594
00:42:52,904 --> 00:42:56,305
That's good. Triumph over tragedy.
Sounds like a John Boorman picture.

595
00:42:56,374 --> 00:42:59,605
Slap a happy ending on it,
the script will write itself.

596
00:42:59,678 --> 00:43:03,273
- Bonnie. Give me the paper.
- l don't know, Larry.

597
00:43:03,348 --> 00:43:05,282
Give it a shot.

598
00:43:06,985 --> 00:43:10,386
'Further bond losses
push Dow down 7.15.'

599
00:43:11,289 --> 00:43:14,053
- l see Connery as Bond.
- That's funny.

600
00:43:14,125 --> 00:43:17,788
lt's a good thing Oliver Stone wasn't
listening to you. Where would we be?

601
00:43:17,862 --> 00:43:22,128
We would have been spared
sitting through Wall Street.

602
00:43:22,200 --> 00:43:25,863
- What did Wall Street do worldwide?
- 70, 75, maybe 80.

603
00:43:25,937 --> 00:43:29,168
$80 million,
a couple Oscars.

604
00:43:29,241 --> 00:43:33,268
l think Larry's point is well taken.
Let's move on.

605
00:43:33,345 --> 00:43:36,837
Can you give us an update
on the Taylor-Hackford project?

606
00:43:36,915 --> 00:43:38,906
Griffin?

607
00:43:38,984 --> 00:43:40,417
Yeah.

608
00:43:41,720 --> 00:43:44,245
l was thinking what
an interesting concept it is...

609
00:43:44,322 --> 00:43:48,622
to eliminate the writer
from the artistic process.

610
00:43:49,561 --> 00:43:54,464
lf we can get rid of the actors and
directors, maybe we've got something.

611
00:43:59,893 --> 00:44:01,326
Hello, Walter.

612
00:44:01,395 --> 00:44:03,693
Make yourself at home.

613
00:44:03,764 --> 00:44:07,495
Mr. Mill, l understand you were late
coming in this morning.

614
00:44:07,567 --> 00:44:09,797
You all right?

615
00:44:09,870 --> 00:44:11,497
l'm fine.

616
00:44:11,571 --> 00:44:13,698
l appreciate your concern.

617
00:44:15,108 --> 00:44:17,508
What can l do for you?

618
00:44:17,577 --> 00:44:21,274
Don't tell me you came here
to pitch me a story?

619
00:44:21,348 --> 00:44:23,748
That's exactly what l've come to do.

620
00:44:23,817 --> 00:44:26,877
lt's a good one, too.
lt's about a writer, sort of.

621
00:44:26,954 --> 00:44:28,387
David Kahane.

622
00:44:31,258 --> 00:44:33,658
Who's David Kahane?

623
00:44:33,727 --> 00:44:37,322
- You met him.
- l meet a lot of writers.

624
00:44:37,397 --> 00:44:42,960
But this writer was murdered last night
in back of the Rialto Theater.

625
00:44:43,036 --> 00:44:44,526
Murdered?

626
00:44:44,604 --> 00:44:48,665
Come to think of it, Pasadena's
as good a place to die as any.

627
00:44:50,043 --> 00:44:51,977
What's the story?

628
00:44:52,045 --> 00:44:56,106
ln 25 words or less?
Okay.

629
00:44:56,183 --> 00:44:59,016
Movie exec calls writer.
Girlfriend says he's at the movies.

630
00:44:59,086 --> 00:45:02,419
Exec goes to movies, meets writer,
drinks with writer.

631
00:45:02,489 --> 00:45:06,050
Writer gets conked and dies
in 4 inches of dirty water.

632
00:45:06,126 --> 00:45:08,424
Movie exec is in deep shit.

633
00:45:09,563 --> 00:45:11,531
What do you think?

634
00:45:11,598 --> 00:45:15,090
That's more than 25 words.
And it's bullshit.

635
00:45:15,168 --> 00:45:19,070
Pasadena homicide doesn't think so.
They've got a complete report.

636
00:45:20,107 --> 00:45:24,373
You met Kahane at the Rialto,
got drunk with him. He left before you.

637
00:45:24,444 --> 00:45:27,743
That's the last time anyone
saw him alive, except you, maybe.

638
00:45:28,949 --> 00:45:31,782
Why are you denying this?

639
00:45:31,852 --> 00:45:35,253
Well, what do the police think?

640
00:45:35,322 --> 00:45:38,086
They think it's a botched robbery.

641
00:45:39,893 --> 00:45:44,887
The window of his car was busted.
He surprised someone taking the radio.

642
00:45:44,965 --> 00:45:47,229
There was a fight, he was killed.

643
00:45:47,300 --> 00:45:50,269
l didn't kill him, Walter.

644
00:45:50,337 --> 00:45:54,899
But l went to see him.
l know l said l didn't, but l did.

645
00:45:54,975 --> 00:45:57,034
Why'd you lie to me?

646
00:45:58,912 --> 00:46:01,278
Now's not a very good time for me.

647
00:46:01,348 --> 00:46:04,875
Haven't you heard the rumors?
l'm on my way out.

648
00:46:04,951 --> 00:46:07,442
Just what l need,
a little more controversy.

649
00:46:07,521 --> 00:46:09,455
lt's not a good time.

650
00:46:10,857 --> 00:46:13,155
Look.

651
00:46:13,226 --> 00:46:16,821
l'm in charge of studio security
in every definition of the word.

652
00:46:16,897 --> 00:46:22,460
Which means it is my job to take care
of a studio executive should he be...

653
00:46:22,536 --> 00:46:25,801
under suspicion of murder
at a time when profits are down...

654
00:46:25,872 --> 00:46:28,272
and the company is vulnerable
for a takeover.

655
00:46:28,341 --> 00:46:31,504
lt is my job to keep this
very, very quiet!

656
00:46:32,913 --> 00:46:35,006
Do you want to help?

657
00:46:35,082 --> 00:46:37,949
- Of course.
- Then stop lying.

658
00:46:38,018 --> 00:46:40,612
- How many times did you meet with him?
- Once.

659
00:46:41,822 --> 00:46:44,347
- Not counting last night.
- Not counting last night.

660
00:46:44,424 --> 00:46:46,688
Why'd you go all the way to Pasadena
to meet him?

661
00:46:46,760 --> 00:46:49,695
He had an idea l was interested in.
l wanted to talk to him right away.

662
00:46:49,763 --> 00:46:54,564
Was his girlfriend a friend, too?
Think fast.

663
00:46:54,634 --> 00:46:57,262
Jesus Christ, Walter.
What is this?

664
00:46:57,337 --> 00:47:00,500
The third degree. Wait until the police
start asking questions.

665
00:47:00,574 --> 00:47:04,032
l'll go to the police now.
You come with me.

666
00:47:04,111 --> 00:47:06,443
You're acting like someone
who's guilty.

667
00:47:06,513 --> 00:47:08,481
You're not guilty, are you?

668
00:47:08,548 --> 00:47:10,778
l'm not a murderer.

669
00:47:28,001 --> 00:47:30,026
Bad news?

670
00:47:30,103 --> 00:47:31,536
What?

671
00:47:31,605 --> 00:47:34,506
The fax.
ls it bad news?

672
00:47:36,977 --> 00:47:38,569
Business as usual.

673
00:47:40,247 --> 00:47:44,013
The Hollywood system
did not murder David Kahane.

674
00:47:44,084 --> 00:47:47,247
Not the $98 million movie,
not the $12 million actor.

675
00:47:47,320 --> 00:47:52,952
Not even the million dollar deal
that David Kahane never landed.

676
00:47:53,026 --> 00:47:56,120
The most that we can pin on Hollywood...

677
00:47:56,196 --> 00:47:59,654
is assault with intent to kill.

678
00:47:59,733 --> 00:48:04,534
Because society is responsible
for this particular murder.

679
00:48:04,604 --> 00:48:06,731
lt is to society we must look...

680
00:48:06,806 --> 00:48:10,537
if we are to have justice
for that crime.

681
00:48:10,610 --> 00:48:13,340
Because someone in the night...

682
00:48:13,413 --> 00:48:15,608
killed David Kahane.

683
00:48:15,682 --> 00:48:18,116
And that person
will have to bear the guilt.

684
00:48:19,653 --> 00:48:22,053
And if David were here now...

685
00:48:22,122 --> 00:48:24,647
l know in my heart
that he would say...

686
00:48:26,092 --> 00:48:28,993
'Cut the shit, Phil.

687
00:48:29,062 --> 00:48:33,021
What did you learn from this?
Did you learn anything from this?(

688
00:48:33,099 --> 00:48:36,193
And l'd say, 'Yeah, David,
l've learned a lot.

689
00:48:36,269 --> 00:48:39,204
We here will take it from here.

690
00:48:39,272 --> 00:48:43,572
And the next time we sell a script
for a million dollars...

691
00:48:43,643 --> 00:48:46,976
and nail some shit-bag producer
to the wall, we'll say...

692
00:48:47,047 --> 00:48:49,515
That's another one for David Kahane.(

693
00:48:53,153 --> 00:48:57,021
David was working on something the day
he died. l'd like to share it with you.

694
00:48:58,391 --> 00:49:01,383
'Blackness.
A mangy dog barks.

695
00:49:01,461 --> 00:49:04,760
Garbage can lids are lifted
as derelicts in the street...

696
00:49:04,831 --> 00:49:07,299
hunt for food.

697
00:49:07,367 --> 00:49:09,801
Buzzing, as a cheap alarm clock
goes off.

698
00:49:09,869 --> 00:49:13,566
lnterior. Flophouse room.
Early morning.

699
00:49:13,640 --> 00:49:16,768
A tracking shot moves
through the grimy room.

700
00:49:16,843 --> 00:49:20,438
Light streams in through holes
in yellowing window shades.

701
00:49:20,513 --> 00:49:23,175
Moths dance
in the beams of light.

702
00:49:23,250 --> 00:49:26,583
Track down along the floor.
The frayed rug.

703
00:49:26,653 --> 00:49:29,588
Stop on an old shoe.

704
00:49:29,656 --> 00:49:31,351
lt's empty.(

705
00:49:35,595 --> 00:49:37,688
That's as far as he got.

706
00:49:39,065 --> 00:49:41,533
That's the last thing he wrote.

707
00:49:42,402 --> 00:49:44,597
So long, Dave.

708
00:49:44,671 --> 00:49:46,866
Fade out.

709
00:49:46,940 --> 00:49:48,373
Thank you.

710
00:50:04,691 --> 00:50:07,182
Who are you?
You're not a writer.

711
00:50:08,928 --> 00:50:11,260
No, l'm Griffin Mill.

712
00:50:11,331 --> 00:50:13,265
We spoke the night David--

713
00:50:13,333 --> 00:50:16,166
Blue sea, white sea.
Yes.

714
00:50:16,236 --> 00:50:18,534
- lt turned out you were right.
- What?

715
00:50:18,605 --> 00:50:21,039
lt was a red sea.

716
00:50:21,107 --> 00:50:22,870
Oh, yeah.

717
00:50:25,312 --> 00:50:28,475
You're the only person l know here.

718
00:50:28,548 --> 00:50:31,415
l'm really sorry about David.

719
00:50:31,484 --> 00:50:34,578
He was a talent.

720
00:50:35,755 --> 00:50:37,950
You really think so?

721
00:50:38,024 --> 00:50:41,289
l always suspected he was...

722
00:50:41,361 --> 00:50:44,023
uniquely untalented.

723
00:50:45,565 --> 00:50:48,728
lt's nice of you to say that. lt was
nice of you to come. You didn't have to.

724
00:50:48,802 --> 00:50:50,235
l did.

725
00:50:50,303 --> 00:50:54,831
You know, l was probably the last person
to see him alive.

726
00:50:54,908 --> 00:50:57,206
The police told me.

727
00:50:57,277 --> 00:50:59,404
Not quite the last, surely.

728
00:51:02,549 --> 00:51:05,780
l'm sure this is a terrible time
for you.

729
00:51:05,852 --> 00:51:08,184
ls there anything you need?

730
00:51:08,254 --> 00:51:12,953
No, really.
l don't feel bad.

731
00:51:13,026 --> 00:51:15,893
lt's like when my parents died.

732
00:51:15,962 --> 00:51:19,489
l didn't feel anything at all.
They were just gone.

733
00:51:21,201 --> 00:51:24,432
l'm sure it hasn't sunk in yet.

734
00:51:24,504 --> 00:51:26,233
That was years ago.

735
00:51:26,306 --> 00:51:29,070
No, l meant David.

736
00:51:29,142 --> 00:51:31,007
Oh, God.

737
00:51:31,077 --> 00:51:34,103
These people.
l don't like it here.

738
00:51:34,180 --> 00:51:37,775
They're all expecting me
to grieve and mourn.

739
00:51:37,851 --> 00:51:40,149
l can't talk to them.

740
00:51:41,888 --> 00:51:47,019
David's gone and
l'm somewhere else already.

741
00:51:47,093 --> 00:51:49,926
- Will you take me home?
- What?

742
00:51:49,996 --> 00:51:52,726
Will you take me home?

743
00:51:52,799 --> 00:51:55,563
Sure. l'm right here.

744
00:52:32,557 --> 00:52:35,185
These are very interesting.
l like them.

745
00:52:35,260 --> 00:52:38,923
- Would you like a drink?
- No, thanks.

746
00:52:38,997 --> 00:52:42,933
Where do you show?
What gallery? Who's your dealer?

747
00:52:43,001 --> 00:52:45,435
l don't have a dealer.

748
00:52:45,503 --> 00:52:48,472
l couldn't sell these.
They're never finished. Biccy?

749
00:52:50,041 --> 00:52:53,010
No, thanks.
They're never finished?

750
00:52:53,077 --> 00:52:57,537
No, they're just what l do
for myself.

751
00:52:57,615 --> 00:53:00,140
What l feel.

752
00:53:00,218 --> 00:53:02,880
You ask lots of questions, Mr. Mill.

753
00:53:02,954 --> 00:53:06,720
Just like the police.
That's all they did, ask questions.

754
00:53:08,426 --> 00:53:10,360
They asked me a lot about you.

755
00:53:10,428 --> 00:53:12,157
Did they?

756
00:53:12,230 --> 00:53:14,164
How long we'd known each other.

757
00:53:14,232 --> 00:53:16,257
lf you'd ever been
to the house before.

758
00:53:16,334 --> 00:53:21,169
- They have to ask those questions.
- l don't see why.

759
00:53:21,239 --> 00:53:23,503
Because that's what police do.

760
00:53:24,542 --> 00:53:27,705
- Can l ask you a question?
- Sure.

761
00:53:27,779 --> 00:53:30,543
Why was it so important
to see David that night?

762
00:53:30,615 --> 00:53:32,708
What was so urgent?

763
00:53:34,385 --> 00:53:37,252
He pitched me a story
a few months ago.

764
00:53:37,322 --> 00:53:39,654
- The Japan story?
- Yes, the Japan story.

765
00:53:39,724 --> 00:53:43,251
l liked it but it needed work,
especially the ending.

766
00:53:43,328 --> 00:53:46,161
l was sitting in my office...

767
00:53:46,230 --> 00:53:49,199
and it suddenly occurred to me
how to make the ending work.

768
00:53:49,267 --> 00:53:51,394
So what was it?

769
00:53:51,469 --> 00:53:52,902
What?

770
00:53:52,970 --> 00:53:55,962
Your idea for the ending.

771
00:53:56,040 --> 00:53:58,031
Up.

772
00:53:58,109 --> 00:54:00,270
Up? What does that mean?

773
00:54:00,345 --> 00:54:03,109
As opposed to down. Moods.

774
00:54:03,181 --> 00:54:06,378
You know, happy as opposed to sad.
Hopeful as opposed to depressing.

775
00:54:06,451 --> 00:54:10,114
- What did you think of his ending?
- l never read it.

776
00:54:12,056 --> 00:54:14,684
- You never read it?
- Nope.

777
00:54:14,759 --> 00:54:17,193
l don't like reading.

778
00:54:17,261 --> 00:54:22,426
- Do you like books?
- l like words and letters.

779
00:54:22,500 --> 00:54:24,764
But l'm not crazy
about complete sentences.

780
00:54:26,537 --> 00:54:29,028
What did he think?

781
00:54:29,107 --> 00:54:32,873
He walked out on me.
l don't think David liked me.

782
00:54:32,944 --> 00:54:36,880
l think he just didn't like
happy endings.

783
00:54:40,618 --> 00:54:42,779
Put your face here.

784
00:54:44,322 --> 00:54:45,755
Great.

785
00:54:47,925 --> 00:54:50,519
What are you doing?
You aren't going to paint me, are you?

786
00:54:50,595 --> 00:54:53,826
l might put you
in one of my paintings.

787
00:54:53,898 --> 00:54:57,561
There's one l want to do
of an lcelandic hero.

788
00:54:57,635 --> 00:55:00,627
He's a thief
and he's made of fire.

789
00:55:00,705 --> 00:55:03,265
- You might not like that.
- Why not?

790
00:55:03,341 --> 00:55:06,071
Because you're in the movies...

791
00:55:06,144 --> 00:55:10,080
and in movies you can't have thieves
as heroes, can you?

792
00:55:10,148 --> 00:55:13,743
l don't know about that. We have a long
tradition of gangsters in movies.

793
00:55:13,818 --> 00:55:17,515
Yes, but they always have to suffer
for their crimes, don't they?

794
00:55:19,123 --> 00:55:21,284
We should pay for our crimes,
shouldn't we?

795
00:55:21,359 --> 00:55:25,693
l think knowing you've committed a crime
is suffering enough.

796
00:55:25,763 --> 00:55:27,754
lf you don't suffer...

797
00:55:27,832 --> 00:55:31,529
maybe it wasn't a crime after all.

798
00:55:31,602 --> 00:55:34,127
Anyway, what difference does it make?

799
00:55:34,205 --> 00:55:37,470
lt has nothing to do
with how things really are.

800
00:55:41,813 --> 00:55:44,475
Do you really believe that?

801
00:55:44,549 --> 00:55:47,950
l don't know what l believe, Mr. Mill.

802
00:55:48,019 --> 00:55:50,817
lt's just what l feel.

803
00:55:52,490 --> 00:55:56,290
You know what you are,
June whatever-your-name-is?

804
00:55:56,360 --> 00:55:58,021
A pragmatic anarchist.

805
00:55:59,464 --> 00:56:01,432
ls that what l am?

806
00:56:01,499 --> 00:56:03,626
l never was sure.

807
00:56:08,105 --> 00:56:10,539
Can l just pick this up?

808
00:56:11,809 --> 00:56:14,573
- Oh, it's heavy.
- Thirty-seven ounces.

809
00:56:14,645 --> 00:56:17,113
Really? Look.

810
00:56:17,181 --> 00:56:21,379
l want to thank my mother, her mother
and her father's mother who--

811
00:56:23,387 --> 00:56:24,820
Hello.

812
00:56:26,257 --> 00:56:29,784
- Meet Detective Susan Avery.
- How do you do? My partner.

813
00:56:29,861 --> 00:56:32,955
- Willa Broom.
- My pleasure. Let's go in here.

814
00:56:33,030 --> 00:56:35,863
This is the first real movie studio
Detective Avery's been to.

815
00:56:35,933 --> 00:56:38,959
- Really?
- Aside from the Universal Tour.

816
00:56:39,036 --> 00:56:41,630
l always take my family there
when they come.

817
00:56:41,706 --> 00:56:45,233
l've been there so often,
l feel like l'm ready to direct.

818
00:56:45,309 --> 00:56:49,837
You'd probably do better
than the film grads these days.

819
00:56:49,914 --> 00:56:52,576
l'm sorry l didn't call you
when l heard Kahane was dead.

820
00:56:52,650 --> 00:56:54,311
- Heard or read?
- Read.

821
00:56:54,385 --> 00:56:57,843
- Why didn't you?
- Walter asked me the same question.

822
00:56:57,922 --> 00:57:01,949
l wish l had a better answer. All
l can say is l didn't think about it.

823
00:57:04,462 --> 00:57:06,555
How did you know where
he was gonna be?

824
00:57:06,631 --> 00:57:09,964
- His wife told me--
- Girlfriend.

825
00:57:10,968 --> 00:57:12,401
Girlfriend.

826
00:57:12,470 --> 00:57:14,665
Girlfriend.
l didn't know either of them.

827
00:57:14,739 --> 00:57:17,105
l was restless,
thought l'd see the movie.

828
00:57:17,174 --> 00:57:20,575
lf he was there, l'd talk to him
about a job l thought he was good for.

829
00:57:20,645 --> 00:57:22,806
You got to the theater,
saw him and?

830
00:57:22,880 --> 00:57:25,542
We had a drink at a Japanese place.

831
00:57:25,616 --> 00:57:29,484
lt was a wild, incredible scene.
lt was like Tokyo.

832
00:57:29,554 --> 00:57:32,421
He left before you.
Why didn't you leave together?

833
00:57:32,490 --> 00:57:35,118
lt was an incredible scene.
l was having a great time.

834
00:57:35,192 --> 00:57:37,057
Why didn't you stay longer?

835
00:57:37,128 --> 00:57:41,326
People stopped singing. Then it was just
a bar and l don't drink.

836
00:57:41,399 --> 00:57:44,334
- You drank with him.
- When in Rome--

837
00:57:44,402 --> 00:57:48,395
Did you know him socially?
Been to his house?

838
00:57:48,472 --> 00:57:50,497
Know anything about him personally?

839
00:57:52,410 --> 00:57:55,345
We'll let you get back to work now.

840
00:57:57,915 --> 00:57:59,906
What's bothering you?

841
00:57:59,984 --> 00:58:02,851
Well, l just have to ask.

842
00:58:02,920 --> 00:58:06,754
Did you see him in the parking lot
after you left?

843
00:58:06,824 --> 00:58:10,419
No, l parked on the street.
l drive a Range Rover...

844
00:58:10,494 --> 00:58:12,928
so l feel safer
when it's visible.

845
00:58:12,997 --> 00:58:15,625
Who's gonna smash a window
if it's on the street?

846
00:58:15,700 --> 00:58:19,158
lf you had a shitty car,
you would've parked in the parking lot?

847
00:58:19,236 --> 00:58:22,137
lf l had a shitty car,
l might be a dead man.

848
00:58:22,206 --> 00:58:25,573
Somehow l think you're too lucky
for that.

849
00:58:25,643 --> 00:58:27,508
Thank you.

850
00:58:27,578 --> 00:58:30,376
Okay, 63, take three. Marker.

851
00:58:31,349 --> 00:58:33,783
Now.

852
00:58:33,851 --> 00:58:35,512
Action!

853
00:58:36,821 --> 00:58:41,087
No, goddamn it, you listen to me!
l've been around a while. l got a nose.

854
00:58:41,158 --> 00:58:44,924
This situation stinks.
lt stinks of the company.

855
00:58:44,996 --> 00:58:48,830
That's right, Peterson,
the fucking ClA. Ever heard of it?

856
00:58:48,899 --> 00:58:51,197
lt's the kind of operation--

857
00:58:51,268 --> 00:58:54,362
You don't understand what he's trying
to go for here.

858
00:58:54,438 --> 00:58:57,373
lt's hard to listen to your argument
when you don't understand.

859
00:58:57,441 --> 00:59:01,901
- Would you shut up, please?
- Kiss my ass!

860
00:59:01,979 --> 00:59:04,311
l have to cut.
My robe cut on the drawer.

861
00:59:04,382 --> 00:59:08,716
- For Christ's sakes!
- l like this guy. He's great.

862
00:59:08,786 --> 00:59:13,689
Waters?
Can l have some Volvic, please?

863
00:59:13,758 --> 00:59:15,783
Yeah, he's great.

864
00:59:17,194 --> 00:59:20,254
l heard the police came to see you
about this dead writer.

865
00:59:20,331 --> 00:59:23,994
- Who was this guy?
- His name was David Kahane.

866
00:59:24,068 --> 00:59:27,094
l never heard of him.
We ever hire him for anything?

867
00:59:27,171 --> 00:59:30,140
l was thinking about it.

868
00:59:30,207 --> 00:59:33,973
He pitched me a story.
l went there to talk to him about it.

869
00:59:34,045 --> 00:59:34,943
Jesus. Poor bastard. Just when his ship
comes in, some bastard blasts him--

870
00:59:34,979 --> 00:59:39,609
Jesus. Poor bastard. Just when his ship
comes in, some bastard blasts him--

871
00:59:39,684 --> 00:59:42,312
l don't want to criticize you...

872
00:59:42,386 --> 00:59:45,412
but l'm supposed to be talking
on the phone.

873
00:59:45,489 --> 00:59:47,354
Are the cops still bothering you?

874
00:59:47,425 --> 00:59:51,919
- No. No, l don't think so.
- Let Stuckel handle it.

875
00:59:51,996 --> 00:59:56,126
We'll give them passes to a screening.
They can sit behind Michelle Pfeiffer.

876
00:59:56,200 --> 00:59:58,395
They'll leave you alone.

877
00:59:59,670 --> 01:00:03,299
A guy named Joe Gillis called.

878
01:00:03,374 --> 01:00:08,038
He wants you to meet him at the
St. James Club at 10:00 on the patio.

879
01:00:08,112 --> 01:00:12,105
- Never heard of him.
- He said you'd know him.

880
01:00:12,183 --> 01:00:14,174
Anybody know who Joe Gillis is?

881
01:00:14,251 --> 01:00:16,947
He's a character William Holden played
in Sunset Boulevard.

882
01:00:17,021 --> 01:00:21,287
- The writer killed by a movie star.
- Gloria Swanson.

883
01:00:25,730 --> 01:00:29,496
Oh, that guy. Last week he said
he was Charles Foster Kane.

884
01:00:29,567 --> 01:00:32,365
A week before that
it was Rhett Butler.

885
01:00:32,436 --> 01:00:35,769
Why would they think l would kill
my own sister's husband?

886
01:00:37,541 --> 01:00:39,705
l was in love with him.

887
01:01:20,779 --> 01:01:25,512
- Griffin? Griffin.
- Malcolm McDowell, good to see you.

888
01:01:25,584 --> 01:01:29,145
Listen. The next time
you want to badmouth me...

889
01:01:29,221 --> 01:01:31,655
have the courage
to do it to my face.

890
01:01:31,723 --> 01:01:34,191
You guys are all the same.

891
01:01:44,536 --> 01:01:46,834
- You love it there?
- l love it. lt's wonderful.

892
01:01:46,905 --> 01:01:49,271
You love your career, don't you?
What is it?

893
01:01:49,341 --> 01:01:53,368
lt was a complete disaster.
Look what happened in Heaven's Gate.

894
01:01:53,445 --> 01:01:54,639
We both are concerned...

895
01:01:54,713 --> 01:01:57,045
about your career.

896
01:01:57,115 --> 01:01:59,811
Where l live, l know how people
think and feel.

897
01:02:00,986 --> 01:02:05,184
Montana will end you.
lt ended Cimino in Heaven's Gate.

898
01:02:05,257 --> 01:02:09,353
- Griffin Mill, hi. Andy Civella.
- Andy, how are you?

899
01:02:09,427 --> 01:02:13,090
l've got Andie MacDowell sitting over
here. You know her. She's so hot.

900
01:02:13,165 --> 01:02:15,429
- Come over and meet her.
- Still living in New York?

901
01:02:15,500 --> 01:02:18,492
l couldn't live here.
l'm allergic to happiness.

902
01:02:18,570 --> 01:02:22,506
Andie, it's good to see you again.
How are the kids?

903
01:02:22,574 --> 01:02:25,008
Great, thanks.
He's wonderful, thank you.

904
01:02:26,344 --> 01:02:28,710
You geniuses know each other.
Tom Oakley.

905
01:02:28,780 --> 01:02:31,840
- Yes, Hi, Tom.
- How are you?

906
01:02:31,917 --> 01:02:35,011
- Funny. l just saw Malcolm McDowell.
- Really?

907
01:02:35,086 --> 01:02:38,419
Roddy McDowall is related
to a cousin of my brother-in-law.

908
01:02:38,490 --> 01:02:41,186
Well, l'm not related
to either one of them.

909
01:02:51,203 --> 01:02:53,194
lf l write it, l direct it.

910
01:02:53,271 --> 01:02:56,707
The last three pictures you directed
were bombs!

911
01:02:56,775 --> 01:03:00,108
Thank you for the drink.
l've got to go.

912
01:03:00,178 --> 01:03:03,807
You've got to go?
We'll walk you to the car.

913
01:03:03,882 --> 01:03:06,316
No, it's okay.
Don't worry about it.

914
01:03:06,384 --> 01:03:08,909
We'd like to buy you a drink.

915
01:03:08,987 --> 01:03:11,979
l can't. l'm meeting someone.
Business.

916
01:03:12,057 --> 01:03:15,220
-We should tell him about Habeas Corpus.
-Of course, but he's a busy man.

917
01:03:15,293 --> 01:03:18,387
- ls there anyone waiting for me?
- No one's asked.

918
01:03:18,463 --> 01:03:22,126
l'm expecting someone.
l'll be out by the pool.

919
01:03:22,200 --> 01:03:25,135
But he'll get back to us.
Right, Griffin?

920
01:04:00,805 --> 01:04:02,238
Oh, sorry.

921
01:04:02,307 --> 01:04:04,969
- Jesus, Andy, it's you.
- Of course it's me.

922
01:04:05,043 --> 01:04:08,410
l can't ask you to join me.
l told you. l'm meeting somebody.

923
01:04:08,480 --> 01:04:11,313
Yeah. You're meeting me.
We got some big business.

924
01:04:11,383 --> 01:04:12,975
You? You?

925
01:04:13,051 --> 01:04:16,817
- Why not me?
- You think this is fucking funny?

926
01:04:16,888 --> 01:04:18,822
What are you talking about?

927
01:04:18,890 --> 01:04:23,520
Wouldn't she make a great Nora? l'd love
to write another Doll's House for her.

928
01:04:23,595 --> 01:04:26,359
Did you meet Tom Oakley?

929
01:04:26,431 --> 01:04:30,697
- Yes. You mean you didn't call me?
- No, l didn't call you.

930
01:04:30,769 --> 01:04:33,670
l'm sorry. l'm really sorry.

931
01:04:34,739 --> 01:04:38,175
Listen, l really am meeting somebody.

932
01:04:38,243 --> 01:04:41,804
There's no way l can hear a pitch
right now. Call me tomorrow.

933
01:04:41,880 --> 01:04:46,977
No, l can't do it tomorrow. l've got
a meeting at Paramount and Universal.

934
01:04:47,052 --> 01:04:48,679
Congratulations.

935
01:04:48,753 --> 01:04:51,085
- lf you don't hear it now, you'll lose.
- Then l lose it.

936
01:04:51,156 --> 01:04:53,317
lt'll take 20 seconds.
When your friend gets here--

937
01:04:53,391 --> 01:04:56,417
- What friend?
- Whoever you're gonna meet.

938
01:04:58,863 --> 01:05:00,831
Twenty-five words or less.

939
01:05:00,899 --> 01:05:04,665
Absolutely. You sit here, Tom.
Go.

940
01:05:05,737 --> 01:05:08,535
- The D.A. is at a moral crossroads.
- Tom! Jesus Christ.

941
01:05:10,275 --> 01:05:13,608
We open outside
the largest penitentiary in California.

942
01:05:13,678 --> 01:05:17,079
lt's night. lt's raining.
A limousine comes through the gate...

943
01:05:17,148 --> 01:05:20,606
past demonstrators holding
a candlelight vigil.

944
01:05:20,685 --> 01:05:24,382
The candles under the umbrellas
glow like Japanese lanterns.

945
01:05:24,456 --> 01:05:27,482
That's nice. l haven't seen that before.
That's good.

946
01:05:27,559 --> 01:05:31,393
A lone demonstrator, a black woman,
steps in front of the limousine.

947
01:05:31,463 --> 01:05:33,761
The lights illuminate her
like a spirit.

948
01:05:33,832 --> 01:05:37,268
Her eyes fix upon those
of the sole passenger.

949
01:05:39,504 --> 01:05:41,438
The moment is devastating
between them.

950
01:05:41,506 --> 01:05:44,737
He's the D.A. She's the mother
of the person being executed.

951
01:05:44,809 --> 01:05:47,403
You're good!
l told you he's good.

952
01:05:47,479 --> 01:05:48,912
Go on.

953
01:05:48,980 --> 01:05:51,574
The D.A. believes
in the death penalty.

954
01:05:51,649 --> 01:05:56,416
And the execution is a hard case.
Black, 19, and definitely guilty.

955
01:05:56,488 --> 01:06:00,948
The greatest democracy in the world, and
36% of people on death row are black.

956
01:06:01,026 --> 01:06:03,051
Poor, disadvantaged black.

957
01:06:03,128 --> 01:06:06,063
He swears the next person
he sees to die...

958
01:06:06,131 --> 01:06:08,497
will be smart, rich and white.

959
01:06:08,566 --> 01:06:12,332
- You, me, whoever.
- What a hook! Beauty hook.

960
01:06:12,404 --> 01:06:14,531
Cut to the chase.

961
01:06:14,606 --> 01:06:18,975
Cut from the D.A. to an up-market
suburban neighborhood.

962
01:06:19,044 --> 01:06:22,411
A couple have a fight.
He leaves in a fit, gets in a car.

963
01:06:22,480 --> 01:06:24,607
lt's the same rainy night.

964
01:06:24,682 --> 01:06:27,412
The car spins out
and goes into a ravine.

965
01:06:27,485 --> 01:06:29,680
The body is swept away.

966
01:06:29,754 --> 01:06:34,817
When the police examine the car, they
find the brakes have been tampered with.

967
01:06:34,893 --> 01:06:38,192
lt's murder, and the D.A. decides
to go for the big one.

968
01:06:38,263 --> 01:06:40,925
He's going to put the wife
in the gas chamber.

969
01:06:40,999 --> 01:06:42,933
But the D.A. falls in love
with the wife.

970
01:06:43,001 --> 01:06:45,265
Of course! But he puts her
in the gas chamber anyway.

971
01:06:46,304 --> 01:06:49,296
Then he finds that the husband
is alive.

972
01:06:49,374 --> 01:06:52,138
That he faked his death.

973
01:06:52,210 --> 01:06:55,441
The D.A. breaks into the prison,
runs down death row...

974
01:06:55,513 --> 01:06:57,572
but he gets there too late.

975
01:06:57,649 --> 01:07:00,117
The gas pellets have been dropped.

976
01:07:00,185 --> 01:07:02,483
She's dead.

977
01:07:02,554 --> 01:07:06,490
l tell you,
there's not a dry eye in the house.

978
01:07:06,558 --> 01:07:08,185
She's dead?

979
01:07:08,259 --> 01:07:13,162
She's dead. She's dead
because that's the reality.

980
01:07:13,231 --> 01:07:16,223
The innocent die.

981
01:07:16,301 --> 01:07:19,361
- Who's the D.A.?
- No one.

982
01:07:19,437 --> 01:07:20,461
No one?

983
01:07:20,538 --> 01:07:23,530
No stars on this project.
We're going out on a limb on one.

984
01:07:23,608 --> 01:07:26,441
Like unknown stage actors...

985
01:07:26,511 --> 01:07:29,173
or maybe somebody English
like what's-his-name.

986
01:07:31,382 --> 01:07:33,247
- Why?
- Why?

987
01:07:33,318 --> 01:07:38,654
This story is too damned important to
risk being overwhelmed by personality.

988
01:07:38,723 --> 01:07:41,351
That's fine for action pictures,
but this is special.

989
01:07:41,426 --> 01:07:43,360
We want real people.

990
01:07:43,428 --> 01:07:46,226
We don't want people coming
with any preconceived notions.

991
01:07:46,297 --> 01:07:50,028
-We want 'em to see a district attorney.
-Bruce Willis.

992
01:07:50,101 --> 01:07:52,763
Not Bruce Willis or Kevin Costner.

993
01:07:52,837 --> 01:07:55,738
This is an innocent woman
fighting for her life.

994
01:07:55,807 --> 01:07:57,775
- Julia Roberts.
- lf we can get her.

995
01:07:57,842 --> 01:07:59,275
We can!

996
01:07:59,344 --> 01:08:03,940
lf l'm perfectly honest,
this isn't even an American film.

997
01:08:06,217 --> 01:08:10,278
- lt's not?
- No. There are no stars.

998
01:08:10,355 --> 01:08:13,119
No pat happy endings,
no Schwarzenegger, no stickups...

999
01:08:13,191 --> 01:08:15,182
no terrorists.

1000
01:08:15,260 --> 01:08:19,060
This is a tough story, a tragedy
in which an innocent woman dies.

1001
01:08:19,130 --> 01:08:23,123
Why? Because that happens!

1002
01:08:25,103 --> 01:08:27,401
Habeas Corpus.

1003
01:08:27,472 --> 01:08:32,205
That's what we're calling it.
'Produce the Corpse.' What do you say?

1004
01:08:33,545 --> 01:08:38,482
-That pitch was more than 25 words.
-But it's brilliant! What's the verdict?

1005
01:08:38,550 --> 01:08:41,815
- Mr. Mill, for you.
- Who gave this to you?

1006
01:08:41,886 --> 01:08:45,219
- l received it at the front desk.
- What is it?

1007
01:08:48,059 --> 01:08:51,654
lt's from the person l was meeting.

1008
01:08:51,729 --> 01:08:53,720
He's not coming.

1009
01:08:53,798 --> 01:08:56,426
Do we have a shot?

1010
01:08:56,501 --> 01:08:59,959
lt's an intriguing idea.
Give me a call at the studio tomorrow.

1011
01:09:00,038 --> 01:09:03,439
There's a scene in Throne of Blood
that has exactly the texture--

1012
01:09:03,508 --> 01:09:07,000
- Tom, just say thank you.
- She has to die! No Hollywood ending.

1013
01:09:07,078 --> 01:09:10,195
Tom, say thank you!

1014
01:11:04,142 --> 01:11:08,875
Fuck! You fucking dog-shit writer!
You fucking tried to kill me!

1015
01:11:32,537 --> 01:11:36,029
Oh, God, you gave me such a scare!

1016
01:11:36,107 --> 01:11:38,974
What are you doing here?

1017
01:11:39,043 --> 01:11:42,877
You gave me such a fright.
Come in.

1018
01:11:42,947 --> 01:11:44,642
Come on in.

1019
01:11:46,484 --> 01:11:50,386
What's the matter?
You look terrible.

1020
01:11:50,455 --> 01:11:51,888
What's up?

1021
01:11:54,392 --> 01:11:56,883
Sit down.
l'll get you a drink.

1022
01:12:07,872 --> 01:12:09,931
Something happened.

1023
01:12:11,109 --> 01:12:15,307
- ls it too late?
- No, it's not too late.

1024
01:12:15,380 --> 01:12:17,541
l don't even know what time it is.

1025
01:12:17,615 --> 01:12:19,378
What's wrong?

1026
01:12:24,689 --> 01:12:29,683
- What are you painting? ls that me?
- Yes, it's you.

1027
01:12:31,329 --> 01:12:32,853
See?

1028
01:12:32,930 --> 01:12:35,057
Do you have snakes in lceland?

1029
01:12:35,133 --> 01:12:37,158
Snakes? No, l don't think so.

1030
01:12:37,235 --> 01:12:39,203
Are you afraid of snakes?

1031
01:12:39,270 --> 01:12:42,239
l don't know.
l've never come close to a real one.

1032
01:12:42,306 --> 01:12:44,934
They scare the shit out of me.

1033
01:12:50,448 --> 01:12:51,938
Have another.

1034
01:12:52,016 --> 01:12:54,382
l don't usually drink.

1035
01:12:57,688 --> 01:13:01,124
Something happened tonight.

1036
01:13:01,192 --> 01:13:02,989
Yes, but...

1037
01:13:05,129 --> 01:13:08,121
there's something else
l have to tell you.

1038
01:13:10,234 --> 01:13:13,397
This isn't easy for me.

1039
01:13:13,471 --> 01:13:14,904
Yes?

1040
01:13:21,879 --> 01:13:24,404
How about if l just get on
with my work...

1041
01:13:24,482 --> 01:13:28,418
and you talk to me
when you feel like it, okay?

1042
01:13:35,693 --> 01:13:38,321
l came very close
to dying tonight.

1043
01:13:41,999 --> 01:13:44,365
All l could think about
was you.

1044
01:13:45,436 --> 01:13:47,996
l don't even know you...

1045
01:13:48,072 --> 01:13:50,973
but you came into my mind.

1046
01:13:54,779 --> 01:13:57,714
l couldn't think of anything else.

1047
01:14:00,151 --> 01:14:03,086
Remember that first night
we spoke on the phone?

1048
01:14:05,289 --> 01:14:09,453
l was outside these windows
watching you and--

1049
01:14:13,664 --> 01:14:16,064
lt was so exciting.

1050
01:14:18,202 --> 01:14:19,999
So new.

1051
01:14:22,340 --> 01:14:23,932
Strange.

1052
01:14:27,311 --> 01:14:30,212
l can't get you out of my mind.

1053
01:14:33,150 --> 01:14:36,313
Are you making love to me?

1054
01:14:38,389 --> 01:14:40,482
Yes, l guess l am.

1055
01:14:42,326 --> 01:14:44,260
l guess l am.

1056
01:14:47,532 --> 01:14:49,898
l want to make love to you.

1057
01:14:57,608 --> 01:14:59,667
lt's too soon.

1058
01:15:02,780 --> 01:15:05,146
lt's too soon, isn't it?

1059
01:15:07,084 --> 01:15:09,678
lt's so strange
how things happen.

1060
01:15:11,689 --> 01:15:13,987
David was here...

1061
01:15:14,058 --> 01:15:16,026
then he left.

1062
01:15:17,128 --> 01:15:18,925
You arrived.

1063
01:15:21,432 --> 01:15:24,458
Maybe it's just the timing,
but l feel like...

1064
01:15:24,535 --> 01:15:27,663
l would go anywhere with you...

1065
01:15:29,407 --> 01:15:31,341
if you asked.

1066
01:15:35,079 --> 01:15:37,479
But we mustn't hurry things.

1067
01:15:37,548 --> 01:15:40,984
We can't hurry things...

1068
01:15:41,052 --> 01:15:43,452
any more than we can stop them.

1069
01:15:45,690 --> 01:15:47,954
l think you better go now.

1070
01:15:48,025 --> 01:15:50,619
l think l'm going to cry now.

1071
01:15:55,032 --> 01:15:57,330
You better go quick.

1072
01:16:03,841 --> 01:16:05,468
l'm sorry.

1073
01:16:05,543 --> 01:16:08,876
No, no, don't be sorry.
Just go home...

1074
01:16:08,946 --> 01:16:12,211
and get some sleep.

1075
01:16:12,283 --> 01:16:14,683
Call me...

1076
01:16:14,752 --> 01:16:16,515
tomorrow.

1077
01:16:17,722 --> 01:16:20,247
lnvite me on a proper date.

1078
01:16:21,325 --> 01:16:23,418
l'd like that.

1079
01:16:38,279 --> 01:16:42,443
Jan? Jan!
Get me Larry Levy on the phone.

1080
01:16:42,516 --> 01:16:45,178
- l don't think he's on the lot.
- Try his car.

1081
01:16:46,253 --> 01:16:49,745
- lsn't he at Fox?
- He used to be. Not anymore.

1082
01:16:49,824 --> 01:16:52,520
l pitched him something
a few months ago. He hated it.

1083
01:16:53,727 --> 01:16:56,025
- That Griffin?
- Yeah.

1084
01:16:56,096 --> 01:17:00,396
Larry, Tom Oakley and Andy Civella
are here. l wouldn't bother you...

1085
01:17:00,467 --> 01:17:02,526
but you should hear their idea now.

1086
01:17:02,603 --> 01:17:05,094
- Hi, guys
- Hi, Larry.

1087
01:17:05,172 --> 01:17:10,166
The voice you'll hear has an English
accent. Tom Oakley. l'm Andy Civella.

1088
01:17:10,244 --> 01:17:12,838
Hi, Andy. l know Tom.
How are you?

1089
01:17:12,913 --> 01:17:15,040
Very well, Larry.
And yourself?

1090
01:17:15,115 --> 01:17:17,174
Fine. What's your story?

1091
01:17:18,285 --> 01:17:21,914
We open outside San Quentin.
lt's night.

1092
01:17:21,989 --> 01:17:23,718
lt's raining.

1093
01:17:23,791 --> 01:17:27,192
A limousine enters through the gate,
past demonstrators...

1094
01:17:27,261 --> 01:17:29,889
holding a candlelight vigil.

1095
01:17:29,964 --> 01:17:33,229
The candles flicker under umbrellas
glowing like Japanese lanterns.

1096
01:17:33,300 --> 01:17:37,031
A lone demonstrator, a black woman,
steps in front of the limousine.

1097
01:17:37,104 --> 01:17:39,698
Her eyes connect
with the lone passenger.

1098
01:17:39,773 --> 01:17:41,832
lt's a devastating moment.

1099
01:17:41,909 --> 01:17:43,774
lncredibly potent.

1100
01:17:46,113 --> 01:17:49,378
No stars. No Schwarzenegger.
No pat Hollywood endings.

1101
01:17:49,450 --> 01:17:53,079
No car chases.
This is an American tragedy...

1102
01:17:53,153 --> 01:17:55,212
in which an innocent woman dies.

1103
01:17:55,289 --> 01:17:58,588
Because that happens.
That's reality.

1104
01:17:59,660 --> 01:18:01,651
Take me off the speaker phone.

1105
01:18:04,899 --> 01:18:09,598
l don't know. lt's a really hot story.
But what is this bullshit, no stars?

1106
01:18:09,670 --> 01:18:13,629
Let me give you a little tip.
Levison came to power on two movies.

1107
01:18:13,707 --> 01:18:16,073
He made $300 million
with no stars in them.

1108
01:18:16,143 --> 01:18:18,577
He will love this idea.
lt'll remind him of his youth.

1109
01:18:18,646 --> 01:18:21,911
His motto used to be
'No stars, just talent.'

1110
01:18:21,982 --> 01:18:25,145
- Has anyone else heard this?
- l don't think so.

1111
01:18:26,020 --> 01:18:27,954
Make a deal now.

1112
01:18:28,022 --> 01:18:31,116
Tomorrow may be too late.
Can we get ahold of Levison?

1113
01:18:31,191 --> 01:18:33,659
Yeah, l'll get Levison.
When can you be back?

1114
01:18:33,727 --> 01:18:35,490
After my AA meeting.

1115
01:18:35,562 --> 01:18:40,295
l didn't realize
you had a drinking problem.

1116
01:18:40,367 --> 01:18:44,997
l don't really, but that's where all the
deals are being made these days. See ya.

1117
01:18:46,540 --> 01:18:48,667
Tom, that was a hell of a pitch.

1118
01:18:50,744 --> 01:18:53,577
Good work.
l think you sold Larry.

1119
01:18:53,647 --> 01:18:55,945
Great! When will we hear?

1120
01:18:56,016 --> 01:19:00,146
Go home, put some champagne on ice.
l'll give you an answer by tonight.

1121
01:19:00,220 --> 01:19:02,017
Jan, come here.

1122
01:19:02,089 --> 01:19:07,026
You move in mysterious ways,
but l like it.

1123
01:19:07,094 --> 01:19:09,062
Did Levy understand? No stars.

1124
01:19:09,129 --> 01:19:11,825
Yes, he was particularly attracted
to that notion.

1125
01:19:11,899 --> 01:19:14,129
- No Hollywood ending?
- No Hollywood ending.

1126
01:19:17,204 --> 01:19:19,434
They looked happy.

1127
01:19:19,506 --> 01:19:22,532
They have a completely fucked-up idea
that has no second act.

1128
01:19:22,609 --> 01:19:25,339
lf l hadn't heard it myself,
l never would've believed it.

1129
01:19:25,412 --> 01:19:28,609
Larry Levy liked it
because he's a dickbrain.

1130
01:19:28,682 --> 01:19:31,048
Levy will sell the idea
to Levison.

1131
01:19:31,118 --> 01:19:33,609
Then l will let Levison have
the brilliant idea...

1132
01:19:33,687 --> 01:19:36,918
of letting Larry
take over the project from me.

1133
01:19:36,991 --> 01:19:38,515
You will?

1134
01:19:38,592 --> 01:19:41,254
Levison can't wait
to get in bed with Levy.

1135
01:19:41,328 --> 01:19:45,594
This piece-of-shit idea
will blow up in both their faces.

1136
01:19:45,666 --> 01:19:50,069
And then l will step in
and save the day.

1137
01:19:52,339 --> 01:19:53,897
Yes!

1138
01:19:55,042 --> 01:19:57,237
Three points.

1139
01:19:57,311 --> 01:19:59,575
Great shot!

1140
01:20:02,983 --> 01:20:04,974
She's receiving the last rites.

1141
01:20:05,052 --> 01:20:07,782
The D.A. discovers that the husband
faked his own death.

1142
01:20:07,855 --> 01:20:11,222
She's innocent. He races to
the penitentiary, but it's too late.

1143
01:20:11,291 --> 01:20:13,782
The pellets have dropped.
She's dead.

1144
01:20:13,861 --> 01:20:16,352
He helped kill the woman he loved.

1145
01:20:16,430 --> 01:20:19,797
- Who are the stars?
- No stars, just talent.

1146
01:20:19,867 --> 01:20:21,892
No stars?

1147
01:20:21,969 --> 01:20:25,735
What the fuck kind of ending
do you call that? lt's depressing.

1148
01:20:25,806 --> 01:20:29,867
Depressing? Terms of Endearment,
Love Story, Steel Magnolias?

1149
01:20:29,943 --> 01:20:32,912
E.T. grossed $319 million
worldwide...

1150
01:20:32,980 --> 01:20:35,107
and there wasn't a dry eye
in the house.

1151
01:20:35,182 --> 01:20:37,616
- Depressing? l don't think so.
- Yeah, but--

1152
01:20:37,684 --> 01:20:40,448
Normally l'd agree with you, but this
is an entirely different kind of deal.

1153
01:20:40,521 --> 01:20:44,389
lt is a matter of taking the risk,
rolling the dice.

1154
01:20:44,458 --> 01:20:47,484
But if they come up 7,
bingo!

1155
01:20:48,595 --> 01:20:51,029
lt's Oscar time.

1156
01:20:51,098 --> 01:20:53,589
- Do they screw?
- Who?

1157
01:20:53,667 --> 01:20:56,135
The D.A. and the woman.
Do they screw?

1158
01:20:56,203 --> 01:21:00,230
lf l'm going to be looking at jail cells
and gas chambers, you need some sex.

1159
01:21:00,307 --> 01:21:03,902
Sure, of course.
We'll get it there. No problem.

1160
01:21:03,977 --> 01:21:06,946
Who's gonna shepherd this thing?

1161
01:21:08,382 --> 01:21:10,942
Larry, you seem to have a good feel
for this. You want to run with it?

1162
01:21:11,018 --> 01:21:14,146
- This project originated with Griffin.
- Bonnie.

1163
01:21:14,221 --> 01:21:16,655
l don't want to dance
at somebody else's wedding.

1164
01:21:16,723 --> 01:21:19,214
lf it's Griffin's project,
it's Griffin's.

1165
01:21:19,293 --> 01:21:22,262
- We should--
- Bonnie, this will have to be my call.

1166
01:21:24,631 --> 01:21:26,565
lt's fine with me.

1167
01:21:26,633 --> 01:21:29,067
My plate is full anyway.

1168
01:21:29,136 --> 01:21:33,470
Larry, it's yours. Hit a home run,
win an Oscar for the home team.

1169
01:21:35,876 --> 01:21:39,243
Griffin, l've got something else
for you. New York tomorrow.

1170
01:21:39,313 --> 01:21:42,771
Tom Wolfe's new book will be in a room
at the hotel. Read it and make your bid.

1171
01:21:42,850 --> 01:21:46,217
Send Bonnie. She'll know if it's
a movie. lf it is, the bid's a million.

1172
01:21:46,286 --> 01:21:49,153
- Me?
- A million! That's high, isn't it?

1173
01:21:49,223 --> 01:21:51,953
lt's Tom Wolfe.
Why not you?

1174
01:21:52,025 --> 01:21:54,550
l'm a story editor.
That's a vice president's job.

1175
01:21:54,628 --> 01:21:57,654
- You don't want to be a vice president?
- Bonnie, pack your bags.

1176
01:21:57,731 --> 01:22:02,361
Congratulations. That was
the most amazing piece l've ever heard.

1177
01:22:02,436 --> 01:22:05,337
- lf you don't want the responsibility--
- No, l'm going.

1178
01:22:05,405 --> 01:22:07,669
l really want to be
one of your soldiers.

1179
01:22:07,741 --> 01:22:11,643
- l'm glad you're on the team.
